 </title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/31/i-set-the-prefered-applications-for-browser-or-e-mail/?answer=32#post-id-32</link><description>I think you are looking for the xdg-open configuration: https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Xdg-open#The_config_file</description><pubDate>Tue, 05 Jun 2012 06:08:10 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/31/i-set-the-prefered-applications-for-browser-or-e-mail/?answer=32#post-id-32</guid></item><item><title>Answer by tab3 for &lt;p&gt;I want to set the default application for some filetypes. If I click on a E-Mail link, i want to fire up Thunderbird. If I download a PDF, evince should come up. Where can I define this kind of behaviour?&lt;/p&gt;
 </title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/31/i-set-the-prefered-applications-for-browser-or-e-mail/?answer=1708#post-id-1708</link><description>Changing xdg setting didn't work for me, but this worked:
`sudo update-alternatives --config x-www-browser`
(should work for Debian/Ubuntu)
</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Apr 2013 10:47:11 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/31/i-set-the-prefered-applications-for-browser-or-e-mail/?answer=1708#post-id-1708</guid></item><item><title>Answer by miguel for &lt;p&gt;I want to set the default application for some filetypes. If I click on a E-Mail link, i want to fire up Thunderbird. If I download a PDF, evince should come up. Where can I define this kind of behaviour?&lt;/p&gt;
 </title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/31/i-set-the-prefered-applications-for-browser-or-e-mail/?answer=35#post-id-35</link><description>There's also a mailcap file that is used to specify which applications should be used for files with different MIME types. It is located at `$HOME/.mailcap` or `/etc/mailcap`.</description><pubDate>Tue, 05 Jun 2012 08:14:01 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/31/i-set-the-prefered-applications-for-browser-or-e-mail/?answer=35#post-id-35</guid></item></channel></rss>